The following components are required for making the project
1. ESP-32 or Node MCU
2. Soil moisture sensor(resistive or capcitive)
3. Relay module
4. Oled display(i2c)
5. Breadboard
6. DHT 11 or DHT 22 temp and humidity sensor
7. Jumper wires
8. power supply 5v (can use a lm2596 regulator set at 5v) or a power bank
9. water pump(optional)
Required Libraries

Install the following libraries in Arduino IDE or PlatformIO:

Blynk (latest version compatible with Blynk IoT)
DHT sensor library
Adafruit GFX
Adafruit SSD1306
Wire (usually pre-installed)

Make sure your ESP32 board package is properly installed and updated.

Blynk Dashboard Setup
Create a new template in Blynk
Set hardware as ESP32
Note down the Auth Token
Create a device from the template
Add the following widgets and assign virtual pins:
Widget Type	Virtual Pin	Purpose
Gauge / Display	V0	Soil Moisture (%)
Gauge / Display	V1	Temperature (°C)
Gauge / Display	V2	Humidity (%)
Switch	V3	Pump Manual Control
Configure the switch (V3):
Mode: Switch
Output: 0 / 1
Upload the code and connect the ESP32 to WiFi
Once connected, data should start appearing on the dashboard
Calibration (Important)
Soil Moisture Sensor

This sensor requires calibration for accurate operation.

Steps:

Insert sensor into dry soil → note the value
Insert sensor into wet soil → note the value
Update the mapping function in code accordingly

Without calibration, the system may overwater or underwater.

Temperature & Humidity Sensor
The DHT11 works for basic monitoring
For better accuracy, consider upgrading to DHT22
Avoid placing the sensor too close to heat sources or water
Circuit & System Understanding
Refer to the circuit diagram in the repository for wiring connections
Refer to the block diagram to understand data flow and system logic

Basic flow:

Sensors → ESP32 → Decision logic → Relay → Pump
Data → OLED display + Blynk app
Power Considerations
Use a stable DC-DC regulator for the ESP32
Avoid powering the pump directly from the ESP32
Ensure proper grounding between all components
Final Notes
Verify sensor readings before relying on automation
Test relay operation separately before connecting the pump
Start with manual control before enabling full automation
